<p>This changed dramatically following the outbreak of the First World War in 1914. The North Eastern Railway, the company that owned the shed, was forced to value women workers as men went abroad to fight. Against fierce opposition from male employees and trade unions, women stepped foot in the engine shed for the first time, typically employed as locomotive cleaners. Sadly, this did not prove a catalyst for change once the war had ended, and women were removed from their posts after the men returned home.<space><space></space></space></p>

